1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:04,660
In this video we're going to talk about electromagnetic waves.

2
00:00:05,759 --> 00:00:08,439
What are electromagnetic waves?

3
00:00:09,580 --> 00:00:12,160
Well, for starters, they're waves.

4
00:00:13,000 --> 00:00:13,699
And what is a wave?

5
00:00:14,439 --> 00:00:20,339
A wave is a disturbance that can carry energy from one place to another.

6
00:00:21,879 --> 00:00:24,079
So here's an example of a wave.

7
00:00:27,500 --> 00:00:31,859
Like all waves, electromagnetic waves, they have amplitude,

8
00:00:34,920 --> 00:00:39,700
they have wavelength, and also frequency.

9
00:00:42,380 --> 00:00:45,799
Electromagnetic waves, they propagate at the speed of light,

10
00:00:46,259 --> 00:00:49,840
which is 3 times 10 to the 8 meters per second.

11
00:00:52,060 --> 00:00:56,899
This speed is equal to the wavelength of the wave times the frequency.

12
00:00:58,640 --> 00:01:03,020
So when the wavelength decreases, the frequency of the wave increases.

13
00:01:04,980 --> 00:01:08,659
The frequency is inversely related to the period of a wave.

14
00:01:09,620 --> 00:01:14,040
The period is the time it takes for the wave to complete one cycle.

15
00:01:15,019 --> 00:01:18,700
The frequency is the number of cycles that it can make in one second.

16
00:01:21,099 --> 00:01:25,459
The unit of frequency is the hertz, and for period it's in seconds.

17
00:01:28,320 --> 00:01:36,599
The energy of an electromagnetic wave is equal to Planck's constant times the frequency.

18
00:01:37,719 --> 00:01:43,040
Planck's constant is 6.626 times 10 to the negative 34,

19
00:01:43,939 --> 00:01:45,180
joules times seconds.

20
00:01:46,560 --> 00:01:49,459
Now, there's a lot of different types of waves in nature.

21
00:01:50,359 --> 00:01:51,299
Think of an ocean wave.

22
00:01:52,260 --> 00:01:54,920
You know, it has a crest, it has a trough.

23
00:01:55,540 --> 00:01:56,640
Think of a wave on a string.

24
00:01:58,260 --> 00:02:00,099
But an electromagnetic wave is different.

25
00:02:00,459 --> 00:02:04,459
This type of wave is composed of electric, eminetic fields.

26
00:02:05,100 --> 00:02:07,159
Thus, we have the name electromagnetic waves.

27
00:02:08,280 --> 00:02:09,300
And let's draw it.

28
00:02:10,199 --> 00:02:13,699
So we're going to draw a 3D coordinate system.

29
00:02:14,640 --> 00:02:19,080
My drawing is not perfect, but I'm going to make the best of it.

30
00:02:19,900 --> 00:02:24,099
So first, let's draw the electric field component of an EM wave.

31
00:02:26,180 --> 00:02:28,960
The electric field oscillates up and down.

32
00:02:33,700 --> 00:02:35,280
We'll call this axis time.

33
00:02:37,480 --> 00:02:43,039
Now, when the electric field is changing, it will create a change in magnetic field.

34
00:02:43,719 --> 00:02:47,580
And the change in magnetic field, in turn, will create a change in electric field.

35
00:02:49,080 --> 00:02:53,620
And so, when you're dealing with an EM wave, you have an electric field on an axis

36
00:02:53,620 --> 00:02:55,219
and perpendicular to it.

37
00:02:55,560 --> 00:02:56,759
You have a magnetic field.

38
00:02:58,120 --> 00:02:59,259
We'll call it B.

39
00:03:06,580 --> 00:03:09,159
So that is an electromagnetic wave.

40
00:03:10,539 --> 00:03:13,560
On one axis, you have the electric field, which are oscillating.

41
00:03:14,060 --> 00:03:18,180
And on another axis, perpendicular to it, you have oscillating magnetic fields.

42
00:03:20,000 --> 00:03:26,139
The electric field is equal to the speed of light times the strength of the magnetic field.

43
00:03:28,980 --> 00:03:33,379
Electromagnetic waves can be created by any type of charge particle.

44
00:03:34,740 --> 00:03:38,719
A charge particle always has an electric field around it.

45
00:03:39,180 --> 00:03:41,599
A moving charge particle can create a magnetic field.

46
00:03:41,599 --> 00:03:48,819
But an accelerating charge particle can create a propagating electromagnetic wave.

47
00:03:54,300 --> 00:03:55,479
Here's another example.

48
00:03:56,219 --> 00:03:57,719
So let's say we have a hydrogen atom.

49
00:03:59,199 --> 00:04:01,379
And let's say this is the first energy level.

50
00:04:01,520 --> 00:04:02,300
This one is the second.

51
00:04:02,840 --> 00:04:04,759
And let's say this is the third energy level.

52
00:04:08,080 --> 00:04:13,860
Let's say we have an electron, an excited electron, in a third energy level.

53
00:04:16,160 --> 00:04:21,879
When the electron drops from the third energy level to the second energy level,

54
00:04:22,600 --> 00:04:23,899
or even lower than that,

55
00:04:24,560 --> 00:04:27,699
any time it goes from a high energy level to a low energy level,

56
00:04:28,339 --> 00:04:31,439
it can emit an electromagnetic wave.

57
00:04:38,039 --> 00:04:40,420
Sometimes it can emit a full ton of light.

58
00:04:42,639 --> 00:04:51,519
Now for the hydrogen atom, the energy of the full ton that's emitted is equal to negative 2.18 times 10 to the negative 18 joules,

59
00:04:52,799 --> 00:04:57,579
times 1 over n final squared minus 1 over n initial squared,

60
00:04:58,220 --> 00:05:02,360
where n is the energy level of the electron.

61
00:05:02,360 --> 00:05:05,279
This is the initial energy level.

62
00:05:05,459 --> 00:05:06,920
In this case that will be n equal 3.

63
00:05:07,420 --> 00:05:08,699
This is the final energy level.

64
00:05:08,819 --> 00:05:10,439
That's where it's going to n equal 2.

65
00:05:12,339 --> 00:05:14,199
When an electron absorbs a full ton,

66
00:05:14,879 --> 00:05:18,079
it can jump from a low energy state to a high energy state.

67
00:05:18,959 --> 00:05:21,899
But when it falls from a high energy state to a low energy state,

68
00:05:21,899 --> 00:05:25,139
it can release a full ton in the form of an electromagnetic wave.

69
00:05:27,420 --> 00:05:28,680
But now only that though,

70
00:05:29,360 --> 00:05:31,379
when electrons are oscillating within the metal,

71
00:05:31,379 --> 00:05:34,879
they can also emit electromagnetic waves.

72
00:05:35,339 --> 00:05:36,120
Even when they're heated,

73
00:05:36,819 --> 00:05:40,839
if you were to heat up metal to a very high temperature,

74
00:05:41,480 --> 00:05:43,899
eventually the metal will appear in red hot.

75
00:05:45,100 --> 00:05:45,899
At this point,

76
00:05:47,279 --> 00:05:51,660
it's emitted in infrared radiation and even in red light as well.

77
00:05:53,199 --> 00:05:54,620
As you raise the temperature,

78
00:05:55,959 --> 00:05:58,620
it'll produce light through incandescence.

79
00:06:00,859 --> 00:06:02,079
It'll appear yellow.

80
00:06:02,699 --> 00:06:03,939
If you raise it even further,

81
00:06:04,240 --> 00:06:05,860
it'll appear bright white.

82
00:06:06,579 --> 00:06:07,720
When the temperature is high,

83
00:06:08,500 --> 00:06:09,620
the atoms are oscillating,

84
00:06:09,699 --> 00:06:10,779
the electrons are oscillating,

85
00:06:11,459 --> 00:06:13,540
and they're emitting electromagnetic waves.

86
00:06:15,680 --> 00:06:19,579
Any time a charged particle is experiencing acceleration,

87
00:06:20,379 --> 00:06:24,980
whether it's moving from a high energy state to a low energy state

88
00:06:24,980 --> 00:06:26,060
or if it's oscillating,

89
00:06:26,060 --> 00:06:29,100
it can emit an EM wave.

